{
  "answer": "**The work is *Andreas* by Cynewulf (old English poetry), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis scene occurs during St. Andrew's sea voyage to rescue St. Matthew from the Mermedonians. Christ, disguised as the helmsman (with two angels as sailors), guides Andrew's ship. Andrew (the saint), unaware of the helmsman's true identity, praises him in a dialogue at sea for his extraordinary skill in stilling the storm and steering the vessel.\n\nAndrew's praise of the helmsman (emphasis added on matching phrases):\n\n> “Never have I met a better seaman,  \n> more skilled in his craft, so it seems to me,  \n> a stronger rower, a shrewder guide,  \n> wiser in his words. [...]  \n> I have been, in my time, now and before,  \n> **sixteen times on a sea-boat**,  \n> my hands frozen while stirring the mere,  \n> the ocean-streams—this is one time more—  \n> yet I have never seen any man,  \n> any son of heroes, who is like to you,  \n> steering at the stern. The stream’s-welling stills,  \n> the surf beats the shore. This boat is so swift,  \n> it fares, **foam-necked, most like a fowl**,  \n> gliding on the ocean. [...]  \n> **You yourself are young**,  \n> shelter of warriors, **not old in winters**,  \n> yet you have in your heart, **you wave-rider**,  \n> the answer of a hero.”[^1]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [Chapter 1](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-ca9772).",
